Ok so it seems like there are three basic cases we need to cover:
1. The user wants to specify a URL (including protocol)
2. The user already has a filesystem initialized and wants to use that to create the FSStore
3. The user already has an FSMap object and want to use that to create the FSStore

I am already uncomfortable with the overloading of the constructor on this class to handle two different scenarios. If we expand it to cover 3, it will get even more messy. A better pattern would be

```python
class FSStore(Store):

    @classmethod
    def from_url(cls, url):
        # figure out fs and path
        return cls(path, fs)

    @classmethod
    def from_fsmap(cls, fsmap):
        # figure out fs and path
        return cls(path, fs)

    def __init__(self, path, fs):
        ...
```
However, this would change the API and break lots of code.

More generally, looking at this code has made me realize that the interface between zarr.storage and FSSpec is not very clean. `FSStore` reimplements and extends many of the MutableMapping methods that `FSMap` implements. `FSStore` calls both `self.map` methods and `self.fs` methods (some of them private 😬 ).

